 <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition" corresp="#Ed">
    <body>
      <head xml:lang="en">Commentary</head>
      <p xml:id="TNV5comm1">e-tu. ciṟu kālamutal ām āṟuṇarttutaṉutaliṟṟu.</p>
<p xml:id="TNV5comm2">naṭuvu paṭṭa viruḷ yāmamuṅ katir kāyum uccip poḻutu mālaip poḻutum pular kālaiyum 
antiyum ēṟpāṭum<!--note place="foot">Print readings make for an awkward list of six times of day which are to be mapped onto 
five landscapes. For this reason and becasue I am, where possible and plausible, taking the 'oldest' reading, I 
have opted for this. In TNVms, the preceding particle '<term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">-ē</hi></term>' doesn't work. Affixing it onto 
an <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">ummai</hi></term> particle is not standard and it doesn't complete any other enumeration in this commentary. There is however a 
problem with this reading - the aspect of the verb is uncomfortable. It would read much better as a perfective
 and were we to take it as a noun, then the <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">ummai</hi></term> particle is not so easily explained. The print would be written identically
  in a palm-leaf MS. Perhaps there is some list of times this is refering to in which we find the print reading 
  enumerated. That would clinch it.</note--> muṟaiyāṉē ain tiṇaikkum ciṟu kāla mutal ām eṉṟa vāṟu.<note>5.</note></p>
      </body>
